census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br>1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/in190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br>1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=QF/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 28,818&nbsp;people, 10,789&nbsp;households, and 7,910&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18137|title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data|accessdate=July 10, 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213022734/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18137|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The population density was {{convert|64.6|PD/sqmi}}. There were 11,952 housing units at an average density of {{convert|26.8|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18137|accessdate=July 10, 2015|title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201139/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18137|archive-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 97.6% white, 0.5% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.2% black or African American, 0.5% from other races, and 0.9% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 1.5% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 43.4% were [[Germans|German]], 14.2% were [[Americans|American]], 13.9% were [[Irish people|Irish]], and 8.7% were [[English people|English]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7c0500000US18137|title=Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=July 10, 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214003507/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7C0500000US18137|archive-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOf the 10,789&nbsp;households, 36.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.1% were married couples living together, 10.2% had a female householder with no husband present, 26.7% were non-families, and 22.8% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.63 and the average family size was 3.08. The median age was 39.2 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $47,697 and the median income for a family was $57,305. Males had a median income of $41,711 versus $31,927 for females. The per capita income for the county was $22,025. About 7.5% of families and 9.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 14.3% of those under age 18 and 8.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7c0500000US18137|title=Selected Economic Characteristics \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=July 10, 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214003447/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7C0500000US18137|archive-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of counties in Indiana]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Ripley County, Indiana]]\n* [http://www.ripleycounty.com - Ripley County website]\n* [https://www.in.gov/core/mylocal/ripley_county.html Ripley County in Indiana portal]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Ripley County, Indiana\n|North     = [[Franklin County, Indiana|Franklin County]]\n|East      = [[Dearborn County, Indiana|Dearborn County]]\n|Southeast = [[Ohio County, Indiana|Ohio County]] and [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]]\n|South     = [[Jefferson County, Indiana|Jefferson County]]\n|West      = [[Jennings County, Indiana|Jennings County]]\n|Northwest = [[Decatur County, Indiana|Decatur County]]\n}}\n\n{{Ripley County, Indiana}}\n{{Indiana}}\n\n{{coord|39.10|-85.26|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IN_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ripley County, Indiana| ]]\n[[Category:Indiana counties]]\n[[Category:1818 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1818]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county           = Ripley County\n| state            = Indiana\n| seal             = \n| founded          = December 27, 1816\n| seat wl          = Versailles\n| largest city wl  = Batesville\n| area_total_sq_mi = 448.06\n| area_land_sq_mi  = 446.43\n| area_water_sq_mi = 1.64\n| area percentage  = 0.37%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop              = 28521\n| density_sq_mi    = 65\n| density_km2      = 24.93\n| time zone        = Eastern\n| footnotes = Indiana county number 69<br>FIPS Code 137\n| named for        = [[Eleazer Wheelock Ripley]]\n| district         = 6th\n| ex image         = Ripley County Courthouse, Versailles, IN (48467486191).jpg\n| ex image cap     = Ripley County Courthouse in Versailles\n}}\n'''Ripley County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located at the southeastern corner of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Indiana]]. According to the 2010 Census, the population was 28,818.<ref name=QF>{{cite web|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/18/18137.html|title=Ripley County QuickFacts|accessdate=September 25, 2011|publisher=United States Census Bureau}}</ref> The [[county seat]] is [[Versailles, Indiana|Versailles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=June 7, 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nRipley County was formed on December 27, 1816, in the same legislative act that created [[Jennings County, Indiana|Jennings County]]. It was named for Gen. [[Eleazer Wheelock Ripley]], an officer in the [[War of 1812]], who figured in the [[Battle of Lundy's Lane]] and the [[Siege of Fort Erie]] during 1814.<ref>{{cite book|author=De Witt Clinton Goodrich & Charles Richard Tuttle|publisher=R. S. Peale & Co.|year=1875|location=Indiana|title=An Illustrated History of the State of Indiana|url=https://archive.org/details/anillustratedhi02tuttgoog|pages=[https://archive.org/details/anillustratedhi02tuttgoog/page/n584 572]}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe county seat of Ripley County is Versailles, Indiana. It was selected as the county seat in 1818, and was laid out in 1819.\n\nAccording to the 2010 census, the county has a total area of {{convert|448.06|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|446.43|sqmi}} (or 99.64%) is land and {{convert|1.64|sqmi}} (or 0.37%) is water.<ref name=\"census-density\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Overview of townships<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18137|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201139/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18137|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|date=|website=factfinder.census.gov|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background: rgb(204, 204, 204);\"\n!Township\n!Established Year\n!Area [[Square mile|mi\u00b2]]\n!Area [[Square km|km\u00b2]]\n!Population\n!Incorporated Towns\n|-\n|[[Adams Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Adams]]\n| align=\"center\" |1858\n| align=\"right\" |43.79\n| align=\"right\" |113.42\n| align=\"right\" |5119\n|[[Batesville, Indiana|Batesville]] (part), [[Sunman, Indiana|Sunman]]\n|-\n|[[Brown Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Brown]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |53.67\n| align=\"right\" |139\n| align=\"right\" |1597\n|\n|-\n|[[Center Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Center]]\n| align=\"center\" |1858\n| align=\"right\" |29.51\n| align=\"right\" |76.43\n| align=\"right\" |2657\n|[[Osgood, Indiana|Osgood]]\n|-\n|[[Delaware Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Delaware]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |33.27\n| align=\"right\" |86.17\n| align=\"right\" |1437\n|\n|-\n|[[Franklin Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Franklin]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |36.6\n| align=\"right\" |94.79\n| align=\"right\" |3773\n|[[Milan, Indiana|Milan]] (part)\n|-\n|[[Jackson Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Jackson]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |29.87\n| align=\"right\" |77.36\n| align=\"right\" |965\n|[[Napoleon, Indiana|Napoleon]]\n|-\n|[[Johnson Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Johnson]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |54.98\n| align=\"right\" |142.4\n| align=\"right\" |3685\n|[[Versailles, Indiana|Versailles]]\n|-\n|[[Laughery Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Laughery]]\n| align=\"center\" |1819\n| align=\"right\" |25.97\n| align=\"right\" |67.26\n| align=\"right\" |4736\n|[[Batesville, Indiana|Batesville]] (part)\n|-\n|[[Otter Creek Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Otter Creek]]\n| align=\"center\" |1858\n| align=\"right\" |41.69\n| align=\"right\" |107.98\n| align=\"right\" |1410\n|[[Holton, Indiana|Holton]]\n|-\n|[[Shelby Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Shelby]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |69.39\n| align=\"right\" |179.72\n| align=\"right\" |999\n|\n|-\n|[[Washington Township, Ripley County, Indiana|Washington]]\n| align=\"center\" |1823\n| align=\"right\" |29.33\n| align=\"right\" |75.96\n| align=\"right\" |2440\n|[[Milan, Indiana|Milan]] (part)\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background: rgb(221, 221, 221);\"\n|'''Ripley County'''\n| align=\"center\" |'''1816'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''448.06'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''1160.471'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''28,181'''\n|\n|}\n\n===Unincorporated towns===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Allen Crossing, Indiana|Allen Crossing]]\n*[[Ballstown, Indiana|Ballstown]]\n*[[Behlmer Corner, Indiana|Behlmer Corner]]\n*[[Benham, Indiana|Benham]]\n*[[Clinton, Ripley County, Indiana|Clinton]]\n*[[Correct, Indiana|Correct]]\n*[[Cross Plains, Indiana|Cross Plains]]\n*[[Cross Roads, Ripley County, Indiana|Cross Roads]]\n*[[Dabney, Indiana|Dabney]]\n*[[Delaware, Indiana|Delaware]] \n*[[Dewberry, Indiana|Dewberry]]\n*[[Elrod, Indiana|Elrod]]\n*[[Friendship, Indiana|Friendship]]\n*[[Haney Corner, Indiana|Haney Corner]]\n*[[Jackson, Ripley County, Indiana|Jackson]]\n*[[Jolleyville, Indiana|Jolleyville]]\n*[[Laughery Switch, Indiana|Laughery Switch]]\n*[[Laugheryville, Indiana|Laugheryville]]\n*[[Lookout, Indiana|Lookout]]\n*[[Morris, Indiana|Morris]]\n*[[Negangards Corner, Indiana|Negangards Corner]]\n*[[New Carrollton, Indiana|New Carrollton]]\n*[[New Marion, Indiana|New Marion]]\n*[[Old Milan, Indiana|Old Milan]]\n*[[Olean, Indiana|Olean]]\n*[[Otter Village, Indiana|Otter Village]]\n*[[Penntown, Indiana|Penntown]]\n*[[Pierceville, Indiana|Pierceville]]\n*[[Prattsburg, Indiana|Prattsburg]]\n*[[Rexville, Indiana|Rexville]]\n*[[Spades, Indiana|Spades]]\n*[[Stringtown, Ripley County, Indiana|Stringtown]]\n*[[Stumpke Corner, Indiana|Stumpke Corner]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Ghost towns===\n*[[Saint Magdalen, Indiana|Saint Magdalen]]\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n*[[Dearborn County, Indiana|Dearborn County]]  (east)\n*[[Decatur County, Indiana|Decatur County]] (northwest)\n*[[Franklin County, Indiana|Franklin County]]  (north)\n*[[Jefferson County, Indiana|Jefferson County]] (south)\n*[[Jennings County, Indiana|Jennings County]] (west)\n*[[Ohio County, Indiana|Ohio County]]  (east\u2013southeast)\n*[[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]]  (at southeast tip)\n\n===Major highways===\n*[[Image:I-74.svg|20px]] [[Interstate 74 in Indiana|Interstate 74]] \u2013 runs east\u2013west across northern tip of county.\n*[[Image:US 50.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 50 in Indiana|US Route 50]] \u2013 runs east\u2013west across middle of county, through Holton and Versailles.\n*[[Image:US 421.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 421 in Indiana|US Route 421]] - enters from Decatur County near northwest tip of Ripley County. Runs SSE to Versailles, then SSW into Jefferson County.\n*[[Image:indiana 46.svg|20px]] [[State Road 46 (Indiana)|State Road 46]] \u2013 runs east\u2013west across northern tip of county, paralleling Interstate 74 on its south side.\n*[[Image:indiana 48.svg|20px]] [[State Road 48 (Indiana)|State Road 48]] \u2013 runs east\u2013west across upper portion of county, through Napoleon.\n*[[Image:indiana 62.svg|20px]] [[State Road 62 (Indiana)|State Road 62]] \u2013 begins at intersection with State Road 129, north of Cross Plains. Runs east through Friendship to Dearborn County.\n*[[Image:indiana 101.svg|20px]] [[State Road 101 (Indiana)|State Road 101]] \u2013 begins at intersection with US Route 50 near east county line. Runs north to Penntown.\n*[[Image:indiana 129.svg|20px]] [[State Road 129 (Indiana)|State Road 129]] \u2013 begins at intersection with State Road 46 east of Batesville, runs south to Versailles, then SSE through Cross Plains into Switzerland County.\n*[[Image:indiana 229.svg|20px]] [[State Road 229 (Indiana)|State Road 229]] \u2013 enters from Franklin County at Batesville, runs SSW to Ballstown then south and west to Napoleon. Runs west to Decatur County.\n*[[Image:indiana 350.svg|20px]] [[State Road 350 (Indiana)|State Road 350]] \u2013 begins at intersection with US 421 at Osgood, runs east through Delaware and Pierceville into Dearborn County.<ref>[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Ripley+County,+IN/@39.2377388,-85.174141,11.5z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x886a5ea2bb16cab9:0x3cae862cc2a01266!8m2!3d39.0986811!4d-85.2308414 ''Ripley County IA'' Google Maps (accessed 16 August 2018)]</ref>\n\n===National protected area===\n* [[Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge]] (part)\n\n==Climate and weather==\n{{climate chart\n|[[Versailles, Indiana]]\n|18|35|3.11\n|21|40|2.71\n|30|51|3.78\n|38|62|4.11\n|47|71|5.27\n|57|79|4.01\n|61|84|3.92\n|59|82|4.55\n|51|76|2.91\n|40|65|3.00\n|32|52|3.09\n|23|40|3.48\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=WX>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIN0685|title=Monthly Averages for Versailles, Indiana|accessdate=January 27, 2011|publisher=The Weather Channel}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in Versailles have ranged from a low of {{convert|18|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|84|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-28|\u00b0F}} was recorded in January 1994 and a record high of {{convert|100|\u00b0F}} was recorded in July 1999. Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|2.71|in}} in February to {{convert|5.27|in}} in May.<ref name=WX/>\n\n==Government==\n{{see also|Government of Indiana}}\nThe county government is a constitutional body, and is granted specific powers by the [[Constitution of Indiana]], and by the [[Indiana Code]].\n\n'''County Council:''' The county council is the legislative branch of the county government and controls all the spending and revenue collection in the county. Representatives are elected from county districts, serving four-year terms. They are responsible for setting salaries, the annual budget, and special spending. The council also has limited authority to impose local taxes, in the form of an income and property tax that is subject to state level approval, excise taxes, and service taxes.<ref name=inc3623>{{cite web|author=[[Indiana Code]]|url=http://www.in.gov/legislative/ic/code/title36/ar2/ch3.html|title=Title 36, Article 2, Section 3|accessdate=September 16, 2008|publisher=IN.gov}}</ref><ref name=inc2102>{{cite web|author=Indiana Code|url=http://www.in.gov/legislative/ic/code/title3/ar10/ch2.pdf|title=Title 2, Article 10, Section 2|accessdate=September 16, 2008|publisher=IN.gov}}</ref>\n\n'''Board of Commissioners:''' The Board of Commissioners is the executive body of the county. Commissioners are elected county\u2013wide in staggered four\u2013year terms. One commissioner serves as board president. They are charged with executing the acts legislated by the council, collecting revenue, and managing the day-to-day functions of the county government.<ref name=inc3623/><ref name=inc2102/>\n\n'''County Officials:''' The county has several other elected offices, including [[sheriff]], [[coroner]], [[auditor]], [[treasurer]], [[Recorder of deeds|recorder]], [[Surveying|surveyor]] and circuit [[court clerk]]. Each of these elected officers serves a term of four years and oversees a different part of county government. Members elected to county government positions are required to declare [[political party|party]] affiliations and to be residents of the county.<ref name=inc2102/>\n\n'''State Government:''' At the State level, Ripley County is divided in its representation. Adams and Laughery Townships are located in the 55th House District which is represented by Rep. Cindy Ziemke.  The rest of Ripley County is located in the 67th district represented by Rep. Randy Frye. Adams and Laughery Townships are in the 42nd Senate District represented by State Senator Jean Leising. The rest of Ripley County is in Senate District 43 represented by Senator Chip Perfect.\n\n'''Federal Government:'''\nRipley County is part of [[Indiana's 6th congressional district]] and is represented in [[United States Congress|Congress]] by [[USRepublican|Republican]] [[Luke Messer]]. Along with the rest of Indiana, its Senators are [[Joe Donnelly]] and [[Todd Young]].\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|first=David|last=Leip|website=uselectionatlas.org|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election|2016]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''75.8%''' ''9,806''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|19.1% ''2,471''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.1% ''658''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''67.9%''' ''7,484''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|29.4% ''3,241''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.6% ''290''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''63.7%''' ''7,794''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Pa